+---
+name: task-craft
+description: Author a high-quality Formic task with duplicate detection, a structured context template, and built-in verification requirements. Use whenever creating or refining a Formic task.
+---
+
+# Task Craft — Formic Task Authoring Protocol
+
+You are crafting a Formic task. A well-crafted task is the single highest-leverage
+artifact in this workflow: vague contexts produced the t-71/t-72/t-73 fix-chain and
+three duplicate decompositions of the same plugin-API epic (t-28–33, t-34–40, t-41–47).
+Follow every step below before outputting a `task-create` block.
+
+## Step 1 — Duplicate check (MANDATORY, do this first)
+
+Before drafting anything, check whether this work already exists or was already done:
+
+1. Search open tasks on the board (Todo / Queued / Review columns in the board state).
+2. Search historical task directories:
+   ```bash
+   ls .formic/tasks/ | grep -i "<2-3 keywords from the request>"
+   ```
+3. Search recent commits:
+   ```bash
+   git log --oneline -30 | grep -i "<keyword>"
+   ```
+
+If a similar task exists **open**: propose updating/re-running it instead of creating a new one.
+If similar work was **already completed**: verify in the code whether the request is actually
+still needed, and tell the user what you found before creating anything.
+
+## Step 2 — Assess complexity and recommend a type
+
+- `quick` — 1–2 files, no design decisions (typos, comments, config tweaks)
+- `standard` — 2–10 files, needs a plan (features, investigated bug fixes, refactors)
+- `goal` — 10+ files or cross-cutting (architect decomposes into 3–8 children)
+
+For `goal` tasks add this line to the context so the architect does not re-create
+existing children: *"Before decomposing, list `.formic/tasks/` and skip any child
+whose scope is already covered by an existing task or committed code."*
+
+State the recommendation with one-line justification before outputting the task.
+
+## Step 3 — Write the context using this template
+
+Every task context MUST contain these five sections:
+
+```
+## Why
+<The problem or motivation. 1-3 sentences. For bugs: observed symptom + how to reproduce.>
+
+## What
+<Concrete requirements. Numbered list. Each item independently checkable.>
+
+## Files
+<Best-guess files to modify (exclusive) and files only read (shared). This feeds the
+declare stage and lease system — be specific, e.g. src/server/services/workflow.ts.>
+
+## Acceptance criteria
+<Numbered, binary pass/fail statements. "Works correctly" is NOT a criterion;
+"GET /api/tasks/:id returns 404 for unknown id" is.>
+
+## Verification
+Before reporting completion, run the quality-gate checklist:
+1. `git diff --stat` is non-empty and touches only declared files
+2. `npx tsc --noEmit` passes
+3. <task-specific test command, e.g. python test/run_tests.py or npx playwright test>
+4. Scan the diff for forbidden practices (no `any`, no `require()`, no missing `.js`
+   extensions on relative imports, no `console.log`, no sync fs, no empty catch)
+Report the actual command outputs as evidence — do not claim completion without them.
+```
+
+## Step 4 — Special rules for bug-fix tasks
+
+If the task fixes a bug, the context must ALSO require (this prevents fix-chains):
+- **Reproduce first**: demonstrate the failure before changing code.
+- **Root cause, not symptom**: state the mechanism ("declare re-runs because
+  `executeDeclareAndAcquireLeases` never checks for an existing declared-files.json"),
+  not the symptom ("declare runs twice").
+- **Sibling scan**: search for other call sites with the same defect pattern.
+- **Regression test**: add a test that fails without the fix.
+
+## Step 5 — Output
+
+Present the recommendation + task in the standard `task-create` code block.
+Priority: `high` only when the bug blocks other queued tasks or corrupts data
+(e.g. board.json corruption); otherwise `medium`.
